! Single-phase step voltage regulator power-flow comparison case.
! (BMOPF subtype: single_phase_autotransformer, ANSI Type B, fixed tap)
!
! Topology: src ──[1-ph regulator, 2.4 kV, 500 kVA, tap=1.05]── reg
!   src.1/4 = source phase + neutral
!   reg.1/4 = regulated phase + neutral
!
! A fixed-tap step voltage regulator is modelled in OpenDSS as a low-impedance
! two-winding transformer with the secondary turns scaled by Tap. A Type B
! regulator at tap ratio a=1.05 boosts the secondary by a (V_reg = a·V_src at
! no load), which matches the BMOPF single_phase_autotransformer with
! tap_ratio=1.05, regulator_type=B (n_eff = 1/a).
!
! %r=0.5 per winding, xhl=1.0  → realistic regulator series impedance so the
! cross-validation exercises the series-drop path, not just the ideal ratio.

Clear

New Circuit.pf_autotransformer basekv=2.4 pu=1.0 angle=0 phases=1 bus1=src.1.0 model=ideal

! Source neutral earthed.
New Reactor.g_src bus1=src.4 bus2=src.0 R=0.001 X=0 phases=1

! Regulator as a 1:1 two-winding transformer with secondary tap = 1.05.
New Transformer.reg phases=1 windings=2
~ wdg=1 bus=src.1.4 conn=wye kv=2.4 %r=0.5 kva=500
~ wdg=2 bus=reg.1.4 conn=wye kv=2.4 %r=0.5 kva=500 tap=1.05
~ xhl=1.0

! Regulated-side neutral earthed.
New Reactor.g_reg bus1=reg.4 bus2=reg.0 R=0.001 X=0 phases=1

! Constant P+Q load (Vminpu=0 Vmaxpu=2 disables ODS voltage-dependent switching).
New Load.ld bus1=reg.1.4 kv=2.4 kw=50 kvar=0 phases=1 model=1 Vminpu=0 Vmaxpu=2

Set VoltageBases=[2.4]
CalcVoltageBases
Solve
